-- PRESS DIGEST-New Zealand newspapers - Sept 12
-- 
-- Thu Sep 11, 2014 03:54PM EDT
-- None



WELLINGTON, Sept 12 (Reuters) - Following are some of the lead stories from New Zealand metropolitan newspapers on Friday.

Stories may be taken from either the paper or Internet editions of the papers. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.  DOMINION POST(www.stuff.co.nz) $6.5m invested in jetpack fundraiser: Martin Aircraft has raised NZ$6.5 million from high-net-worth investors for developing its "jetpack" flying machine as it continues to mull an initial public offering. - - - - Turners goes to Peru for grapes: Turners & Growers <TUR.NZ> has signed a joint venture with Chilean fruitgrower Unifrutti to grow table grapes in Peru. - - - - Talisman's stockpiles hold first gold in decades: Dual-listed New Talisman Gold Mines <NTL.NZ> says stockpiled ore from its Talisman site on the Coromandel Peninsula shows encouraging grades of gold per tonne of material. - - - - NZ firm named in huge European scam: New Zealand shell companies may have played a part in the biggest money-laundering operation in Eastern Europe. - - - -  NEW ZEALAND HERALD (www.nzherald.co.nz) Winston on the rise as signs point to tighter race: New Zealand First is on the rise and seems assured of returning to Parliament in bigger numbers, according to the latest Herald-DigiPoll survey. And Labour appears to have arrested its steady decline. - - - - Downtown revamp to cost NZ$500m: Auckland will get something special for the downtown area from the sale of Queen Elizabeth Square by Auckland Council, says Precinct Properties <PCT.NZ> chief executive Scott Pritchard. Precinct is planning to spend about NZ$500 million redeveloping the Downtown Shopping Mall into a 36-storey commercial tower rising from a three-storey retail podium. - - - - Labour's tax plan centre stage for our CEO's: Labour's proposal for a capital gains tax was centre stage at a New Zealand Herald Mood of the Boardroom breakfast in Auckland yesterday.  Nearly 54 per cent of respondents in a Mood of the Boardroom survey saw merit in a capital gains tax but there was trenchant opposition to Labour's plan to raise the top marginal tax rate to 36 per cent. - - - -